<TITLE> Rising Afghanistan make first-class breakthrough </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Aug 27 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Afghanistan took another big step in an unlikely rise through the cricketing ranks, scoring their first first-class game win in a thrilling effort over hosts Netherlands. The Asian side claimed a tense one-wicket win in an Inter-Continental Cup four-day game Wednesday, emerging with flying colours in a tournament meant to provide non-Test playing associate nations experience in the longer format. In a rain-hit game in Amstelveen, Afghanistan scored 209 for nine to achieve their second innings target with more than a day to spare. They drew their opening first class game, versus a Zimbabwe XI, earlier this month, an International Cricket Council statement said. Afghanistan grabbed sporting headlines earlier this year when the team from the war-ravaged nation defied the odds and a lack of cricketing pedigree by reaching the final stages of the qualifiers for the 2011 World Cup. Although they could not finish among the top four who qualified from the final tournament, their sixth spot earned them one-day international status for at least the next four y
